			<outline text="June 6" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 14:51:48 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="06">
				<outline text="I'm writing a little app that archives my tweets in JSON-flavored OPML, just to see what might happen. If I put stuff in double-square brackets, for example, might a [[knowledge base]] pick it up and do something interesting with it? Hmmm. :-)" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 15:33:48 GMT" type="outline" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1401562845201027075"/>
				<outline text="Is JSON easier to read than XML?" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:41:20 GMT" type="outline" description="It's actually impossible to know.">
					<outline text="Maybe: JSON is easier to read than XML." created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:41:30 GMT" flNumberedSubs="true">
						<outline text="JSON is generally arranged as an outline, " created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:42:18 GMT"/>
						<outline text="JSON generally has more whitespace, better arranged, " created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:42:21 GMT"/>
						<outline text="XML is more dense, and" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:42:25 GMT"/>
						<outline text="Lists are easier to read vertically than horizontally.&quot;,                                    " created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:42:28 GMT"/>
						</outline>
					<outline text="However there are no rules about how either JSON or XML are arranged, where the whitespace goes, how indentation works, or even if there is any whitespace or indentation, so it's possible to create totally unreadable data in either format.                                " created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:43:25 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&quot;curly&quot;" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 16:43:34 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Electric Drummer screen shot" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 14:51:49 GMT" type="outline" description="It's nice when the software you've been dreaming about is suddenly usable for what you designed it for.">
					<outline text="A progress report on &quot;Drummer&quot;.  " created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 14:51:55 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Drummer is mainly a web app, but it is also a desktop app for the Mac known as Electric Drummer." created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 15:02:06 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The whole thing is coming along nicely. I've been using ED for a couple of weeks now, and find it's way better than any other outliner I've used for web writing. It should be, it's the newest, and has lots of promising features. But it's really nice when the software you've been dreaming about, and working hard to create, is suddenly usable for what you designed it for. Electric Drummer is there now. Yippee!" created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 15:06:58 GMT"/>
					<outline text="To celebrate, here's a &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/images/2021/06/06/edScreenShot.png&quot;&gt;screen shot&lt;/a&gt; of my workspace. " created="Sun, 06 Jun 2021 15:08:30 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 5" created="Sat, 05 Jun 2021 13:57:45 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="05">
				<outline text="Today was the day I was dreaming of in the depth of winter." created="Sat, 05 Jun 2021 13:57:46 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I don't hate the Nets for any reason other than they are (I hope) the last instance of a superteam, a concept pioneered by LeBron James, whose career as a superteam founder is now over, btw, as of this week. Basketball is a sport. I know it's also a business, but I don't give my heart to businesses. Sorry." created="Sat, 05 Jun 2021 14:43:25 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I think I'm going to have to write a &lt;i&gt;this.how&lt;/i&gt; piece about breaking users, and all the times people have learned the hard way that breaking users or developers is total misery for everyone, so don't do it. Examples: Python, Font-Awesome. Here's the &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1401189014997278725&quot;&gt;thread&lt;/a&gt;. " created="Sat, 05 Jun 2021 14:38:10 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_Treatment&quot;&gt;In Treatment&lt;/a&gt; is like getting therapy yourself. " created="Sat, 05 Jun 2021 21:52:09 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 4" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2021 15:52:39 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="04">
				<outline text="All of a sudden Chrome is adding a &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/images/2021/06/04/chromeBlackBar.png&quot;&gt;weird black thing&lt;/a&gt; to tabs in my browser window. I have no idea what it's supposed to mean." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2021 19:22:53 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/TechEmails/status/1400208754659008519&quot;&gt;A great demo&lt;/a&gt; for how outlines work in planning meetings. It would have worked even better if they projected the outline and updated it in real time as people discussed.  " created="Fri, 04 Jun 2021 19:11:08 GMT" type="outline" urltweet="https://twitter.com/TechEmails/status/1400208754659008519"/>
				<outline text="From my point of view, tech is drowning in too many ways to do the same thing, at all levels." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2021 16:37:52 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Why does every efficiency in the USPS result in breaking users? Calling attention to the fact that the management isn't trying to provide a reliable service. I suppose the silver lining is it means we'll migrate away from the post office more. Burn less carbon." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2021 15:52:40 GMT" type="tweet" tweetId="1400843168334163968" tweetUserName="davewiner"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 3" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:39:44 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="03">
				<outline text="Jason Shellen found a Google podcasts app on the web. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 18:38:30 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Trump's blog was pretty awful, but it was functional, and clearly it flopped, which itself is interesting data about the power of Twitter. Trump ought to thank them for being  there, there would be no &quot;President Trump&quot; w/o Twitter." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 18:36:27 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="News orgs insist we pay them rent, the same price no matter how much you use them, where users probably would prefer to pay for news as we pay for food or electricity, based on what we use. Ultimately I think we're all losing, but most people refuse to pay the rent." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 18:13:02 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="The announced-today &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theverge.com/2021/6/3/22464291/twitter-blue-subscription-service-canada-australia-undo-reader-mode&quot;&gt;Twitter subscription service&lt;/a&gt; is blah in its current form but I bet this is just the beginning. I believe there will be a revenue-sharing program for news orgs. An integration of their stories with Twitter. If they do it right it doesn't have to be a silo, btw." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:39:45 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="[[Drummer]] docs tease" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:52:52 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="&quot;Drummer&quot; has a built-in doc server. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:52:59 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&quot;Frontier&quot; users will find this UI familiar, it's an improved version of the verb docs server we have in Frontier. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:57:23 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Drummer's scripting philosophy, like Frontier's, is that apps not only have user interfaces, they also have scripting interfaces. Which means theoretically, anything you can do with a mouse and keyboard you could also do in a script. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:53:31 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The first app I've created a scripting interface for is Twitter, because I use it so much, and so many other people do. I felt it could immediately benefit from being scriptable. I haven't covered anything like the whole functionality of Twitter, it wouldn't even be possible because their API doesn't cover it all, but -- a lot is possible with the verb set we have working right now. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:54:19 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Screen shot of Drummer's docs UI." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:55:37 GMT" inlineImage="http://scripting.com/images/2021/06/03/docserverScreen.png"/>
					<outline text="" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 14:55:55 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 2" created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 12:41:50 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="02">
				<outline text="Well &lt;a href=&quot;https://nypost.com/2021/06/02/knicks-season-ends-with-blowout-playoff-loss-to-hawks/&quot;&gt;this was&lt;/a&gt; a great Knicks season. Lots of good stuff to build on." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 02:20:47 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="This is kind of important. Logseq now exports OPML. If you &lt;a href=&quot;http://littleoutliner.com/?url=http://instantoutliner.com/pg&quot;&gt;click this link&lt;/a&gt;, their outline will open in LO2. Seeing their outline open in my world is revealing to say the least. This is like joining two cultures. The Mac outlining culture with the &quot;other&quot; culture (to me) which derives from &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Org-mode&quot;&gt;Org-mode&lt;/a&gt; (i am told) and wikis. I can see some interesting cross-fertilization happening." created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 17:09:55 GMT" type="outline" image="http://scripting.com/images/2020/05/26/cherries.png"/>
				<outline text="About Logseq: I love their energy, how quickly they got on board with OPML. There are lots of things I want to show that we can do &lt;a href=&quot;http://this.how/opmlChecklist/&quot;&gt;with OPML&lt;/a&gt;. Most important it's all about the open web, connecting people's virtual minds, not just everyone on their own island." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 02:52:32 GMT" type="outline" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1400277400882135041"/>
				<outline text="I'm watching &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_Treatment&quot;&gt;In Treatment&lt;/a&gt;. It's kind of appalling how people trod all over the therapist's boundaries. They project wildly on him. He should get combat pay. " created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 17:18:49 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="The Brooklyn Nets are not a real basketball team. They are just a shell that Kevin Durant pwned by signing with them. Kind of the way Apple didn't really buy NeXT, it was the other way around. Anyway, the Durant's &quot;Nets&quot; might win a title, or try a couple of times, but either way the train will move on and leave the Nets as wrecked as the Cleveland Cavaliers. This is a trend, it's no longer innovative, curious, fun or even good basketball. Durant was bored in Golden State. He'll get bored in Brooklyn too. Imho, they're boring right now. :boom:" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 02:41:35 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="And btw, what kind of lame name is &quot;Nets&quot; anyway?" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2021 02:47:57 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="It's fresh cherry season! Next up: fresh peaches. " created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 16:28:56 GMT" type="tweet" tweetId="1400523561639481357" tweetUserName="davewiner"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.radcliffe.harvard.edu/news-and-ideas/ruth-bader-ginsburg-tells-young-women-fight-for-the-things-you-care-about&quot;&gt;Ruth Bader Ginsburg&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Fight for the things that you care about, but do it in a way that will lead others to join you.&quot; I'm guessing she didn't know, but she was promoting a very powerful idea for technology." created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 14:33:31 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Yesterday I wrote &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2021/06/01/141749.html?title=naomiOsakaDerrickRose&quot;&gt;about Derrick Rose&lt;/a&gt; as a 32-year-old star athlete, and as if to prove my point, he was quoted in today's &lt;a href=&quot;https://nypost.com/2021/06/01/knicks-can-keep-magical-season-going-just-a-little-longer/&quot;&gt;NY Post&lt;/a&gt; saying: â€œIâ€™m 32 years old. I never talked shit like that in my whole life. Iâ€™m not going to start now once &lt;a href=&quot;https://nypost.com/2021/06/01/clint-capela-goes-scorched-earth-on-dirty-knicks-in-epic-taunt/&quot;&gt;Clint Capela&lt;/a&gt; starts talking crazy. Iâ€™m too old for that shit, bro.â€ I love this guy. If any Knick could boast, it's DR, but he's cool. He likes playing for the Knicks, and we like him. " created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 12:41:51 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I don't think the Biden Administration should be negotiating with Republicans about anything." created="Wed, 02 Jun 2021 13:00:27 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 1" created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 12:29:10 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="01">
				<outline text="If we were doing this right, free journalism training would be available to anyone who wants it. An investment in our way of life. The same way Covid vaccinations are free. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 16:27:38 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Insulting Trump does no good for anyone. Right now is time to take him seriously. There's going to be another insurrection in August. They're doing some very loud dog whistling now." created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:56:04 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I'm &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1399712537298587652&quot;&gt;posting&lt;/a&gt; links to real-world &lt;a href=&quot;http://this.how/opmlChecklist/&quot;&gt;OPML&lt;/a&gt; files to help build familiarity with the format." created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:18:34 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I started watching the HBO series &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_Treatment&quot;&gt;In Treatment&lt;/a&gt;. At first it's boring, but it develops as it goes along. Some of the most despicable characters become sympathetic, and vice versa. You see real love between some of the pairs, also a lot of fear. 90 percent is conversations in a therapist's office. I found it hard to imagine how that could work, but it does. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:39:24 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="A segment this morning on NPR, a discussion between two alumni of &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_E._Lee_High_School_(Jacksonville)&quot;&gt;Robert E Lee High School&lt;/a&gt; in Jacksonville, FL. It's in northeast Florida, an area I'm fairly familiar with, my uncle used to live in the area. It's more like rural Georgia than most of Florida. The thing that hasn't gotten through to the whites there is that slavery is still ongoing in the US. They can't yet relate to the blacks as fellow Americans. If they could, they could understand the history they cherish was slavery to the blacks. They were considered property, animals, they could be killed with impunity. Asked how he would feel if it were Adolf Hitler High School, he said it was nothing like that, but it is &lt;i&gt;exactly&lt;/i&gt; like that, only the Third Reich lasted only 13 years. American slavery lasted &lt;i&gt;250&lt;/i&gt; years. Renaming a high school is a very small step. When we are fully reconciled, all of us will see the slaves of America as our ancestors. In the South they resist even beginning going down that path. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 12:29:11 GMT" type="outline" image="http://scripting.com/images/2021/04/18/roots.png"/>
				<outline text="My thinking was influenced by parents and grandparents who barely escaped Germany in WWII spending the rest of their lives trying to figure out WTF happened. If we live through something like that we'll learn a lot. But if their experience means anything, probably far more questions than answers." created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:46:37 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Naomi Osaka &amp; Derrick Rose" created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:17:49 GMT" type="outline" metaImage="http://scripting.com/images/2018/09/10/naomiOsaka.png" description="In 10 or 20 years ask her how she does it, she'll probably have some answers. ">
					<outline text="There's a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KeVca9MwDX8&quot;&gt;great scene&lt;/a&gt; in Bull Durham where the veteran teaches the rookie how to talk to reporters. It's all cliches. &quot;Of course it's boring,&quot; says the pro, &quot;that's the point.&quot;  " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:17:56 GMT" image="http://scripting.com/images/2021/06/01/derrickRose.png"/>
					<outline text="It's a ridiculous ritual. Esp with a star as young as &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naomi_Osaka&quot;&gt;Naomi Osaka&lt;/a&gt;. She has incredible talent, but when you're so young, in her case 23, most of it is intuitive, not well-understood. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:21:34 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I've seen that recently in interviews with Knicks star &lt;a href=&quot;https://nypost.com/2021/04/21/how-derrick-rose-has-transformed-knicks-from-upstarts-to-winners/&quot;&gt;Derrick Rose&lt;/a&gt;. The questions reporters ask are still insipid, but at 32, having been a huge star at 22, &lt;a href=&quot;https://therookiewire.usatoday.com/2021/05/03/bulls-derrick-rose-youngest-player-nba-mvp/&quot;&gt;youngest MVP ever&lt;/a&gt;, then having his &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derrick_Rose#2011%E2%80%9312:_ACL_tear&quot;&gt;body break&lt;/a&gt; over and over, he had to learn how it works, and now his play still has a lot of the spark he had when he was young, and even better, now he can tell you how he manages it, something he probably could not have done at 22. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:21:43 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I find at my advanced age, in a &quot;sport&quot; where you body's age doesn't matter (up to a point, see this blog in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2002/06.html&quot;&gt;summer&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2002/07.html&quot;&gt;of&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2002/08.html&quot;&gt;2002&lt;/a&gt;), I have a much better understanding of how I do what I do than when I was an ambitious star in my 20s. I can tell you a lot more how this works than I could then, when I just had an intuitive sense of how it worked. Enough of that intuition was right so that I could make it to the next stage, and the one after that, and so on." created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:22:41 GMT"/>
					<outline text="In software, very few people stick with it through their whole career as I have. Companies still have no idea how age and tech work co-relate. But we know a lot about tennis, and basketball. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:23:17 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Naomi Osaka is brilliant, wonderful, a joy to behold. You can see it, read it, in everything she does and says. Her intuition says she should be allowed to be introspective while she tries to win in her sport. Her intuition is incredibly compelling. I feel of her as I do of a great movie &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jennifer_Lawrence&quot;&gt;star&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quentin_Tarantino&quot;&gt;maker&lt;/a&gt;, or software developer. In 10 or 20 years ask her how she does it, she'll have some answers. Right now it's probably not possible. " created="Tue, 01 Jun 2021 14:23:33 GMT"/>
					<outline text="My opinion only. "/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
